name: Nancy Pelosi
content:
Today, our nation celebrates nine years of the landmark DACA initiative, which empowers hundreds of thousands of young immigrants to pursue their American Dream. This week, we also mark one year since the Supreme Court affirmed DACA and rejected the Trump Administration‚Äôs illegal, immoral assault on our Dreamers. As we celebrate these joyous anniversaries, we are reminded of the urgency we face in fully protecting these Americans, so they can continue to strengthen our nation with their talents, hard work and patriotism.

The Democratic House has now proudly passed H.R. 6, the American Dream and Promise Act, twice. This landmark legislation will put Dreamers and TPS and DED recipients on a permanent pathway to citizenship. The Senate must now swiftly pass this legislation into law. We also salute President Biden for his immediate executive actions upon taking office to ensure that, in the meantime, DACA is stronger today than ever before.

Dreamers make America more American, from studying at our universities to serving our nation overseas to fighting this pandemic on the frontlines. To mark this momentous anniversary and honor our nation‚Äôs heritage as a land of immigrants, House Democrats call on our Republican colleagues to join us in supporting the Dream and Promise Act so that this vital legislation will become the law of the land.

name: Terri Sewell
content:
My brothers and I were blessed to have an amazing mother who blazed trails in education, public service, and community activism. As the first Black Councilwoman for the City of Selma, Nancy Gardner Sewell paved the way for the journey that now I have the privilege to travel as Alabama‚Äôs first Black Congresswoman.

My mother was the epitome of a servant leader from her more than 50-year commitment to serving underprivileged children in the Alabama Blackbelt to holding international positions in her beloved Alpha Kappa Alpha Sorority, Inc. and to her lifelong dedication to uplifting the Selma-Dallas County community. We know that our mother, Nancy Gardner Sewell, sowed many seeds and that her legacy will live on in the many lives that she impacted.

Join me in honoring her memory and uplifting her legacy. Updated information regarding this weekend's Celebration of Life Services can be found below.

name: Doug LaMalfa
content:
Earlier today, a bill I helped write the Preventing Disaster Revictimization Act, passed the house unanimously by voice vote. This bipartisan bill will prevent the U.S. Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) from seeking reimbursement from Pacific Gas and Electric‚Äôs (PG&E) $13.5 billion settlement fund that was set aside for wildfire victims. Further, it will prevent FEMA from taking back disaster assistance funds resulting from a settlement claim or legal action, or that it mistakenly awarded to victims who applied for assistance in good faith and utilized that money to help rebuild their lives. Under current law, FEMA can come back weeks, months, or even years later to seek repayment of funds it awarded victims if it detects an over-payment or believes payments have become duplicative.

The government has no business raiding the disaster compensation fund and obstructing the recovery efforts of fire victims. This bill will ensure that no disaster victim will have their hard-fought compensation stripped from them by the federal government under the guise of reimbursing themselves on the backs of those who have suffered.

name: Sam Graves
content:
Following the Flood of 2019, a lot of folks had trouble getting the help they needed in Northwest Missouri.

In one case, FEMA awarded one man individual assistance money to fix his family home that had been destroyed.

He followed all the rules. He was honest, open, and transparent with FEMA. That didn‚Äôt stop the agency from coming back and demanding that he pay that $12,000 back.

It wasn‚Äôt because he committed fraud. It was because FEMA made a ‚Äúmistake.‚Äù They told him he didn‚Äôt REALLY qualify for that help.

Unfortunately, his story is all too common with FEMA. They do this all the time. They give honest, innocent disaster victims assistance, only to demand the money back, weeks, months, or even years later.

That‚Äôs wrong. Not only does this make it difficult for these disaster victims to rebuild their lives, but it also scares others out of spending the FEMA money they get to fix their homes.

After all, are you going to spend $12,000 in disaster assistance to fix your house if you‚Äôre scared FEMA is going to knock on your door one day and demand you pay every penny back?

My bill, the Preventing Disaster Revictimization Act, puts a stop to this nonsense. It requires FEMA to forgive these debts when there‚Äôs no fraud committed. It goes further than that though. It holds FEMA accountable for these mistakes and requires the agency to take steps to prevent future errors.

name: Chris Van Hollen
content:
The Capital Beltway is not unlike many major highways in the United States. It was built in the 1960s and its construction tore through a thriving Black community. The Gibson Grove community, a post-Emancipation Black settlement in Maryland had been partially inhabited by formerly enslaved people who created a local society to provide health care, host funeral processions, and build a network to support each other. The Morningstar Moses Hall Cemetery, established in 1885, served as the final resting place for many in the Gibson Grove community, but was later partially seized by the federal government for the construction of the Capital Beltway. Stories like this are all too common in the United States. As we work to right the wrongs of our past ‚Äì and shine a light on this history of inequity ‚Äì we also must protect historic sites like this one, which has been designated one of the nation‚Äôs ‚Äú11 Most Endangered Historic Places for 2021‚Äù by the National Trust for Historic Preservation. I have urged the Federal Highway Administration to avoid physical impacts to the Moses Hall property and the Gibson Grove A.M.E. Zion Church as part of any agreement to construct new lanes on the Beltway moving forward.

MARYLANDMATTERS.ORG
Cemetery Near Controversial Road Project is Among Nation‚Äôs ‚ÄòMost Endangered‚Äô ‚Äì Maryland Matters

Under Speaker Nancy Pelosi's orders, the U.S. House has been shut down to the public for 15 months. name: John Garamendi
content:
Today I hosted a virtual ceremony to honor the participants of my 2021 Congressional High School Art Competition. Every year I‚Äôm always amazed by the incredible talent and quality of art we receive for the competition.

This year‚Äôs first-place winner was Fayola Fayusi of Armijo High School in Fairfield for her piece, ‚ÄúHeroes Like Me.‚Äù Fayola‚Äôs work will be featured at an exhibit at the U.S. Capitol for a year, and she won a pair of plane tickets to travel to Washington, DC to attend a ceremony with the winners from Congressional Districts across the country.

This year‚Äôs runner-up was Alexandra Gionco of Marysville Charter Academy for the Arts for her piece, ‚ÄúLove Us Like You Love Our Food.‚Äù Alexandra‚Äôs work will be featured in my Washington, DC office for a year.

This competition is a team effort. Our panel of independent judges performed the tough task of narrowing down the winners. Teachers, parents, and mentors worked behind the scenes to offer encouragement, advice, and inspiration. And most importantly, these students knew they were artists and photographers with something important to say. Congratulations to everyone who participated in this year‚Äôs Congressional High School Art Competition

name: Gregory F. Murphy
content: Today is National Megalodon Day, a fun day that helps us learn about the most massive shark that has ever lived. There is no better place to learn about these prehistoric creatures than right here in eastern NC at the Aurora Fossil Museum. Founded in 1976, this science education resource center is a great place to learn about the natural history of Eastern North Carolina. I had the honor of recently being present for the ribbon cutting for the grand reopening. This museum welcomes more than ten thousand people each year from across all 50 states and proudly displays the remnants of a Megalodon. More details can be found by visiting http://aurorafossilmuseum.org/

name: Doug Lamborn
content:
Last week, I visited Springs Rescue Mission. Maj. Gen. (Ret.) Jack Briggs, President and CEO of Springs Rescue Mission, and staff met with me to discuss challenges they face and solutions they find for those most in need.

The Springs Rescue Mission provides an essential service to those most in need in the Pikes Peak region. Their mission of 'meeting people where they are' means no one is left behind, and everyone receives the opportunity to get back on their feet. This non-profit organization provides critically needed food, shelter, clothing, and services to our neighbors experiencing homelessness, poverty, and addiction. Springs Rescue Mission is an excellent example of government, business, and faith-based entities collaborating to solve community problems.

During the visit, I honored Larry Yonker, in his retirement from Springs Rescue Mission, after decades of service by presenting him with a Congressional Record. The CR recognizes Larry's vision for a Community of Hope for the most vulnerable men and women of Colorado Springs and his steadfast faith.

Congratulations to Larry on his retirement, and special thanks to Maj. Gen. (Ret.) Jack Briggs and staff for the insightful tour and for the critical work you do caring for our community.

name: Michael F. Q. San Nicolas
content:
Presented Admiral John Menoni with an official Capitol Flag and entered official remarks on the Congressional Record for his service as Commander of Joint Region Marianas.

Today was a Change of Command ceremony where we bid him farewell to his new post, and welcomed Admiral Nicholson.

The service of Admiral Menoni during his tenure was exemplary, not only in his ability to achieve mission but to take on unforeseen circumstances and navigate them like a true Sailor.

Most notably, Admiral Menoni redefined the role of Joint Region Command in his unparalleled engagement and collaboration with local leadership, coupled with his shrewd diplomacy on issues of contention.

He will be missed, and we are grateful for his service.

Photo includes myself and Admiral Menoni during the presentation, with Vice Admiral Merz, Commander of the 7th Fleet observing.

name: David P. Joyce
content:
Human trafficking is a real problem in Ohio, one that has long been poorly understood. While we have learned how to more accurately identify and respond to cases of human trafficking more appropriately over the years, there's more work to be done.

From my time as a prosecutor to the past several years serving as the Co-Chair of the House's Bipartisan Task Force to End Sexual Violence, I know that when it comes to human trafficking, the importance of education and training efforts cannot be overstated. That's why I cosponsored H.R. 2795, the DHS Blue Campaign Enhancement Act.

The U.S. Department of Homeland Security Blue Campaign is a national public awareness campaign designed to educate the public, law enforcement and other industry partners to recognize the indicators of human trafficking and how to appropriately respond to possible cases. Specifically, this legislation would require the Director of the Blue Campaign to develop web-based interactive training videos and provide online training opportunities for federal, state, local, tribal, and territorial law enforcement officers. It would also require the development of effective awareness tools to be distributed to industry partners (including airlines, hotels, medical professionals, etc) to help individuals outside of law enforcement identify and prevent instances of human trafficking.

With Ohio ranking among the 10 worst states in the nation for human trafficking, it is critical that we boost education and awareness efforts surrounding these crimes and their victims. Learn more about this important bill here: https://bit.ly/35lgpao

content: For years, we‚Äôve worked to get the National Children's Museum officially up and running in our nation‚Äôs capital ‚Äì after it had already served our communities in various capacities for decades. name: Bradley Scott Schneider
content:
I believe that words matter and that they have consequences. Elected officials, and especially members of Congress, have a great responsibility to carefully measure our words and be as precise as possible when we communicate. Sometimes we may stumble in our message. When we do, we should be given the chance to clarify exactly what we intended to say and promptly set the record straight.

But when I heard Representative Marjorie Taylor Greene initially make her comparison of our nation‚Äôs Covid-response to the Holocaust, and then repeat it again and again, I never expected a retraction or an apology. After all, Rep. Greene has a long history of unapologetically inflammatory and dangerous rhetoric. I was therefore pleasantly surprised to learn that she made the time to visit the Holocaust Memorial Museum (where I have the honor of serving as a trustee), and I appreciate that after her visit she understood the harm of her comparison and offered an apology.

In light of her apology, I am electing not to go forward at this time with introducing a resolution of censure.

Moving forward, I will continue to call out harmful or dangerous rhetoric by my colleagues, irrespective of which side of the aisle from which it emanates. While I will certainly have vehement disagreements with Rep. Greene on policy, politics, and style, I hope that Congress can take the necessary steps to serve as a model to a nation desperately in need of leaders willing to correct themselves when they are wrong, and to engage in a more civil discourse to ultimately work together toward a ‚Äòmore perfect union.‚Äô

I want to thank the co-leads of our would-be Censure Resolution for their work: Representatives Linda S√°nchez, Nikema Williams, and Brenda Lawrence. Words matter, but so do actions. By speaking up, we were hopefully able to inspire Rep. Greene to reconsider her remarks in the context of the singular horrors of the Holocaust.

name: Garret Graves
content:
Our bill to advance restoration of the Lake Pontchartrain Basin passed through the U.S. House.

More than 1/3 of Louisianans live in the Lake Pontchartrain Basin ‚Äì fishing its lakes, boating along its waterways, building businesses and growing their families with its resources.

It is quintessential Louisiana and helps make our state one of the best places to live in and visit in America.

Our bill provides federal support for the important work of improving the ecological health of Lake Pontchartrain and surrounding lakes and waterways to preserve critical habitat for shrimp, blue crab, trout, flounder and other resources that the area provides for South LA and the nation.

Louisiana sits at the bottom of the funnel for the largest drainage system in North America and bears the brunt of flooding, water management and other challenges that the Mississippi River Watershed‚Äôs 32 states and 2 Canadian provinces send our way, like diverting floodwaters into Lake Pontchartrain through the Bonnet Carre Spillway for a record-setting 5 times in 5 years.

This bill helps ensure we can rise to that challenge and continue the work needed to protect, preserve, and promote the health of Lake Pontchartrain and the success of this nationally important region. I also want to say thank you Whip Steve Scalise, Congressman Troy Carter and former Congressman Cedric Richmond for their support and leadership on this bill as we look forward to it becoming law.

https://garretgraves.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/graves-bill-restore-lake-pontchartrain-basin-passes-us-house

name: Garret Graves
content:
Our bill to expedite airport infrastructure projects passed through the U.S. House.

By incentivizing early completion of airport projects, this bill will help ensure that airports have the tools necessary to avoid delayed service and get airport improvement projects done faster.

We need to make sure our airports are ready to handle the increase in travel ‚Äì whether vacations, leisure or business trips. This legislation takes successful, existing road project programs and implements the same efficient practices to get airport improvement projects completed faster, meaning we will improve the efficiency and capacity of our airports while handling a runway or taxiway that is temporarily out of service.

Overall, this is a win-win for airports and taxpayers alike. I‚Äôm looking forward to seeing this bill result in more efficient use of taxpayer funds, better flight options, and improved aviation safety.

Read more about it here:

This effort is allowing us to open back up today. With the reopening today, this will be the last update on COVID statistics in our district I post, unless things change. Currently, the global shipping industry is able to discriminate against American exporters. This unfairly hurts the U.S. shipping industry, agricultural exporters, and other vital businesses that are willing to pay to ensure American-made products reach markets throughout the world.

Unfortunately, the Federal Maritime Commission currently lacks the legal authority from Congress to ensure U.S. exporters have the opportunities that other exporters throughout the world enjoy.

Trade must be mutually beneficial, and Congress needs to give the Federal Maritime Commission clear direction and legal authority to ensure fairness.

name: Neal P. Dunn
content:
Helpful information from the Bay County Sheriff's Office for those traveling this summer -\-\

Bay County Sheriff's Office
13 hrs ¬∑

SUMMER HOME CHECK GEARS UP FOR YOUR VACATION

June 15, 2021

So now that many people are making plans for a summer getaway, even if just for a three-day weekend, how do you keep your home safe while you are gone?

The Bay County Sheriff‚Äôs Office has a plan in place. It‚Äôs the Summer Home Check program. Simply call the Sheriff‚Äôs Office at 850-747-4700, and ask for Dispatch. The telecommunicator in Dispatch will take your information down and send someone to check on your home while you are away.

The BCSO also has some tips for those who will be away from home for a week or longer:

Cut back bushes around windows so you don‚Äôt give cover to anyone who may try to get inside through a window.

Install flood lights that are motion sensitive around your home.

Cut off mail delivery while you are gone so a full mailbox doesn‚Äôt signal the fact you are out of town. Do the same if you receive newspaper delivery. Or make plans to have someone pick up anything you have delivered to your house while you are away.

Put lamps inside your home on a timer so it will appear someone is at home while you are away.

The Summer Home Check program will send a marked vehicle by your home regularly to get out and check around the home. Call 850-747-4700 to schedule your home for the Summer Home Check extra patrol.

###
Prepared by R. Corley
Information by Capt. S. Harbuck

name: Don Young
content:
I‚Äôm proud to be an original cosponsor of the Firearm Due Process Protection Act. This vital legislation would implement an enforcement mechanism for Americans to ensure their Second Amendment rights are restored when wrongly denied by our federal government.

Each year, the federal government unjustifiably denies thousands of law-abiding citizens the ability to purchase a firearm because of errors within the National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS). Mismatched fingerprints and inaccurate criminal records are common issues that result in someone having to file an appeal when attempting to purchase a firearm.

Additionally, NICS errors disproportionately affect minorities by rejecting background checks due to cultural spellings. With over 200 languages spoken in our state, it is critical that Alaska Natives and others are not denied their Second Amendment rights simply because NICS is ill-equipped to process the spelling of their names.

This bill provides needed oversight, and will give Americans the legal recourse they deserve.

name: Gregorio Kilili Camacho Sablan
content:
One hundred thirty-two emergency housing vouchers from the American Rescue Plan have been allocated to help individuals and families in the Marianas, who are homeless or at risk, move into safe, stable homes. The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development made the announcement Thursday. Issuance of the emergency housing vouchers will be the responsibility of the Northern Marianas Housing Corporation. The Rescue Plan covers both the cost of the vouchers and the related administrative costs, including up-front costs to stand up the program for an initial 18-month period. HUD will continue to cover the cost of the vouchers in 12-month increments through September 30, 2030 or until the $5 billion Rescue Plan funding runs out, whichever comes first.

Read more about the program and eligibility:
https://www.hud.gov/sites/dfiles/PIH/documents/EHV_FAQ_v3_06092021.pdf

name: Tom Cole
content:
During Alzheimer‚Äôs and Brain Awareness Month, we remember that many families have felt the heartbreaking impact of Alzheimer‚Äôs disease in some way. Sadly, more than six million Americans are currently suffering with the disease. Throughout this month, we recognize this national health crisis and draw attention to efforts to slow down, prevent and ultimately find cures for Alzheimer‚Äôs and other forms of dementia.

Like many across the country, my family knows all too well the heartbreaking decline that takes place in those suffering with this disease. During the last several years of my father‚Äôs life, my family watched helplessly as he became a different person and slowly lost a lifetime of memories throughout the various stages of Alzheimer‚Äôs.

Unfortunately, the Alzheimer‚Äôs Association recently reported that Alzheimer‚Äôs and dementia-related deaths increased 16 percent during the coronavirus pandemic. Even before this rapid increase, this national health crisis carried enormous financial and human costs, straining both public and private budgets. In fact, it is credited as the most expensive disease in the United States. By 2050, Alzheimer's is projected to cost our country more than $1.1 trillion, even before inflation. That is more than three times the government spending under Medicare and Medicaid and in out-of-pocket spending.

However, I am encouraged that steps have been taken to provide some hope and find answers. As the top Republican leader on the appropriations subcommittee responsible for health spending, I have always been a staunch supporter and advocate for increasing funding for dedicated Alzheimer's disease research at the National Institutes of Health. When I chaired the panel, I was proud to shepherd and help secure historic funding increases for this worthy cause ‚Äì quadrupling federal support from $600 million a year to $3.1 billion this year.

Thanks to Congress prioritizing and delivering more funding for biomedical research, there have been promising developments in the fight against Alzheimer‚Äôs in recent months and years. Just this month, the Food and Drug Administration approved a new drug created to slow cognitive decline in those suffering with the disease ‚Äì this is the first new drug to treat Alzheimer‚Äôs since 2003. Because of these advancements and others to come, we must keep up the momentum. Indeed, for my part, I remain dedicated to working with my colleagues on both sides of the aisle to build on and further boost research funding that could lead to lifesaving clues, answers and treatments.

This Congress, I am proud to cosponsor the Alzheimer‚Äôs Caregiver Support Act, which authorizes grants to public and non-profit organizations to expand training and support services for families and unpaid caregivers of patients with Alzheimer‚Äôs or other forms of dementia. I am also a cosponsor of the Comprehensive Care for Alzheimer's Act, which would pilot a new dementia care management model that would provide comprehensive care management services to Medicare beneficiaries with Alzheimer‚Äôs.

Unfortunately, there are still a lot of unknowns about the cause of Alzheimer‚Äôs as well as why and how it progresses. In the quest for answers and treatments, we must continue to prioritize funding as well as advocate for the quality of life for patients. If we can find answers and solutions for Alzheimer‚Äôs, the entire nation will be better off.

This is an important step towards full Senate passage. Watch live here: https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/meetings/hr6-american-dream-and-promise-act-of-2021
